    "content": "# How to Use This Deep Handbook\n\nThis version is not only a PDF-to-HTML conversion. It is a **deep interview study app** for the JD you shared: full-stack ownership, Python/Flask/FastAPI, React/TypeScript/Redux, REST APIs, auth, databases, queues, webhooks, debugging, and system architecture.\n\n## How to prepare with it\n\n1. **First pass:** read the topic explanation and understand the mental model.\n2. **Second pass:** run the code examples locally.\n3. **Third pass:** answer the interview questions without reading the answer.\n4. **Fourth pass:** build the mini-projects at the end.\n\n## The JD is checking these things\n\n| JD phrase | What they may test |\n| --- | --- |\n| logically strong | Can you break down behavior step-by-step? |\n| own features end-to-end | Can you explain frontend → API → DB → worker → response? |\n| REST APIs | HTTP methods, status codes, validation, pagination, idempotency |\n| async/event-driven | Webhooks, retry, queue, worker, idempotency key, dead-letter queue |\n| MongoDB/PostgreSQL | Schema design, indexes, transactions, aggregation, query tuning |\n| auth | JWT vs session, cookies, OAuth, refresh tokens, CSRF/XSS |\n| debugging production issues | Logs, traces, correlation IDs, reproduction, rollback, metrics |\n\n## One system-flow answer you should master\n\n```text\nUser clicks button in React\n  → component state changes or Redux action dispatches\n  → API call goes with Authorization header or cookie\n  → backend middleware validates CORS, auth, request body\n  → controller/path operation calls service layer\n  → service starts DB transaction if needed\n  → data is written to PostgreSQL/MongoDB\n  → event/job is published to Redis/BullMQ/Kafka if async processing is needed\n  → worker consumes the job, calls third-party API/webhook/payment/telephony\n  → worker updates status and logs result\n  → frontend polls, receives websocket update, or refetches data\n```\n\n**Interview language:** “I don’t only think in terms of API endpoints. I think in terms of data movement, state transitions, consistency, retry behavior, and failure handling.”",
