    "content": "# Python Mental Model: Execution, Objects, Memory\n\nPython interviews are rarely about memorizing syntax. They are about whether you understand **how Python behaves at runtime**.\n\n## Python is dynamically typed, but strongly typed\n\n```python\nx = 10        # x refers to an int object\nx = \"hello\"   # now x refers to a str object\n\n# Strong typing: Python won't silently convert incompatible types\nprint(\"5\" + 5)  # TypeError\n```\n\nDynamic typing means variable names can point to different object types over time. Strong typing means Python does not blindly mix incompatible types.\n\n## Names vs objects\n\n```python\na = [1, 2]\nb = a\nb.append(3)\nprint(a)  # [1, 2, 3]\n```\n\n`a` and `b` are names pointing to the same list object. This is why mutable values can surprise you.\n\n## Mutable vs immutable\n\n| Type | Mutable? | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| int , float , bool | No | Reassignment creates/refers to another object |\n| str , tuple , frozenset | No | Contents cannot be changed |\n| list , dict , set | Yes | Can be modified in place |\n| custom objects | Usually yes | Unless designed immutable |\n\n```python\nx = \"abc\"\ny = x\nx += \"d\"\nprint(y)  # abc, because strings are immutable\n\narr = [1, 2]\nother = arr\narr += [3]\nprint(other)  # [1, 2, 3], list mutated in place\n```\n\n## Identity vs equality\n\n```python\na = [1, 2]\nb = [1, 2]\n\nprint(a == b)  # True: same value\nprint(a is b)  # False: different objects\n```\n\nUse `is` for singleton identity checks like `None`, not normal value comparison.\n\n```python\nif value is None:\n    ...\n```\n\n## LEGB scope rule\n\nPython resolves names in this order:\n\n1. **Local**\n2. **Enclosing**\n3. **Global**\n4. **Built-in**\n\n```python\nx = \"global\"\n\ndef outer():\n    x = \"outer\"\n    def inner():\n        x = \"inner\"\n        print(x)\n    inner()\n\nouter()  # inner\n```\n\n## global and nonlocal\n\n```python\ncount = 0\n\ndef inc_global():\n    global count\n    count += 1\n\ndef make_counter():\n    count = 0\n    def inc():\n        nonlocal count\n        count += 1\n        return count\n    return inc\n\ncounter = make_counter()\nprint(counter())  # 1\nprint(counter())  # 2\n```\n\nUse `nonlocal` for closures; use `global` rarely because global state makes testing/debugging harder.\n\n## Shallow copy vs deep copy\n\n```python\nimport copy\n\noriginal = [[1], [2]]\nshallow = copy.copy(original)\ndeep = copy.deepcopy(original)\n\noriginal[0].append(99)\nprint(shallow)  # [[1, 99], [2]]\nprint(deep)     # [[1], [2]]\n```\n\nShallow copy copies only the outer container. Deep copy recursively copies nested objects.\n\n## Interview questions\n\n**Q: Why is default mutable argument dangerous?**\n\n```python\ndef add_item(item, bucket=[]):\n    bucket.append(item)\n    return bucket\n\nprint(add_item(1))  # [1]\nprint(add_item(2))  # [1, 2] surprise\n```\n\nDefault arguments are evaluated once when the function is defined, not every time it is called.\n\nCorrect:\n\n```python\ndef add_item(item, bucket=None):\n    if bucket is None:\n        bucket = []\n    bucket.append(item)\n    return bucket\n```",
    "searchText": "python python mental model: execution, objects, memory python mental model: execution, objects, memory python interviews are rarely about memorizing syntax. they are about whether you understand how python behaves at runtime . python is dynamically typed, but strongly typed dynamic typing means variable names can ... # python mental model: execution, objects, memory python interviews are rarely about memorizing syntax. they are about whether you understand **how python behaves at runtime**. ## python is dynamically typed, but strongly typed ```python x = 10 # x refers to an int object x = \"hello\" # now x refers to a str object # strong typing: python won't silently convert incompatible types print(\"5\" + 5) # typeerror ``` dynamic typing means variable names can point to different object types over time. strong typing means python does not blindly mix incompatible types. ## names vs objects ```python a = [1, 2] b = a b.append(3) print(a) # [1, 2, 3] ``` `a` and `b` are names pointing to the same list object. this is why mutable values can surprise you. ## mutable vs immutable | type | mutable? | notes | | --- | --- | --- | | int , float , bool | no | reassignment creates/refers to another object | | str , tuple , frozenset | no | contents cannot be changed | | list , dict , set | yes | can be modified in place | | custom objects | usually yes | unless designed immutable | ```python x = \"abc\" y = x x += \"d\" print(y) # abc, because strings are immutable arr = [1, 2] other = arr arr += [3] print(other) # [1, 2, 3], list mutated in place ``` ## identity vs equality ```python a = [1, 2] b = [1, 2] print(a == b) # true: same value print(a is b) # false: different objects ``` use `is` for singleton identity checks like `none`, not normal value comparison. ```python if value is none: ... ``` ## legb scope rule python resolves names in this order: 1. **local** 2. **enclosing** 3. **global** 4. **built-in** ```python x = \"global\" def outer(): x = \"outer\" def inner(): x = \"inner\" print(x) inner() outer() # inner ``` ## global and nonlocal ```python count = 0 def inc_global(): global count count += 1 def make_counter(): count = 0 def inc(): nonlocal count count += 1 return count return inc counter = make_counter() print(counter()) # 1 print(counter()) # 2 ``` use `nonlocal` for closures; use `global` rarely because global state makes testing/debugging harder. ## shallow copy vs deep copy ```python import copy original = [[1], [2]] shallow = copy.copy(original) deep = copy.deepcopy(original) original[0].append(99) print(shallow) # [[1, 99], [2]] print(deep) # [[1], [2]] ``` shallow copy copies only the outer container. deep copy recursively copies nested objects. ## interview questions **q: why is default mutable argument dangerous?** ```python def add_item(item, bucket=[]): bucket.append(item) return bucket print(add_item(1)) # [1] print(add_item(2)) # [1, 2] surprise ``` default arguments are evaluated once when the function is defined, not every time it is called. correct: ```python def add_item(item, bucket=none): if bucket is none: bucket = [] bucket.append(item) return bucket ```"
