    "content": "# Python Functions: Args, Closures, Decorators, Generators\n\n## Function arguments\n\n```python\ndef create_user(name, age=18, *roles, active=True, **metadata):\n    return {\n        \"name\": name,\n        \"age\": age,\n        \"roles\": roles,\n        \"active\": active,\n        \"metadata\": metadata,\n    }\n\nprint(create_user(\"Asha\", 25, \"admin\", \"editor\", city=\"Delhi\"))\n```\n\n| Syntax | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| name | required positional/keyword argument |\n| age=18 | default argument |\n| *roles | collects extra positional args into tuple |\n| active=True | keyword-only argument after *roles |\n| **metadata | collects extra keyword args into dict |\n\n## Positional-only and keyword-only arguments\n\n```python\ndef f(a, b, /, c, *, d):\n    print(a, b, c, d)\n\nf(1, 2, c=3, d=4)\n# a and b must be positional\n# d must be keyword-only\n```\n\nUseful when designing clean APIs.\n\n## First-class functions\n\n```python\ndef shout(text):\n    return text.upper()\n\nfunc = shout\nprint(func(\"hello\"))\n```\n\nFunctions can be assigned, passed as arguments, and returned.\n\n## Closures\n\n```python\ndef multiplier(factor):\n    def multiply(value):\n        return value * factor\n    return multiply\n\ndouble = multiplier(2)\nprint(double(10))  # 20\n```\n\nThe inner function remembers variables from its enclosing scope.\n\n## Decorators\n\nA decorator wraps another function.\n\n```python\nfrom functools import wraps\n\ndef log_calls(fn):\n    @wraps(fn)\n    def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n        print(f\"Calling {fn.__name__}\")\n        result = fn(*args, **kwargs)\n        print(f\"Finished {fn.__name__}\")\n        return result\n    return wrapper\n\n@log_calls\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a + b\n\nprint(add(2, 3))\n```\n\n`@log_calls` is equivalent to:\n\n```python\nadd = log_calls(add)\n```\n\n### Decorator with arguments\n\n```python\nfrom functools import wraps\n\ndef require_role(role):\n    def decorator(fn):\n        @wraps(fn)\n        def wrapper(user, *args, **kwargs):\n            if role not in user[\"roles\"]:\n                raise PermissionError(\"Forbidden\")\n            return fn(user, *args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n\n@require_role(\"admin\")\ndef delete_user(current_user, user_id):\n    return f\"deleted {user_id}\"\n```\n\n## Generators\n\nGenerators produce values lazily.\n\n```python\ndef read_large_file(lines):\n    for line in lines:\n        if line.strip():\n            yield line.strip()\n\nfor item in read_large_file([\"a\\n\", \"\\n\", \"b\\n\"]):\n    print(item)\n```\n\nWhy useful?\n\n- memory efficient\n- stream processing\n- infinite sequences\n- pipelines\n\n## Generator expression\n\n```python\nsquares = (x * x for x in range(10))\nprint(next(squares))\nprint(next(squares))\n```\n\n## yield from\n\n```python\ndef chain_lists(lists):\n    for items in lists:\n        yield from items\n\nprint(list(chain_lists([[1, 2], [3, 4]])))\n```\n\n## Interview questions\n\n**Q: Difference between list comprehension and generator expression?**\n\n```python\nnums = [x * x for x in range(1_000_000)]  # builds list immediately\nnums_lazy = (x * x for x in range(1_000_000))  # produces lazily\n```\n\nUse generator expression when you do not need all values in memory at once.\n\n**Q: Why use `functools.wraps` in decorators?**\n\nWithout `wraps`, the wrapped function loses metadata like `__name__`, `__doc__`, annotations, and this can break debugging, docs, and frameworks.",
    "searchText": "python python functions: args, closures, decorators, generators python functions: args, closures, decorators, generators function arguments syntax meaning --- --- name required positional/keyword argument age=18 default argument roles collects extra positional args into tuple active=true keyword-only argument after roles m... # python functions: args, closures, decorators, generators ## function arguments ```python def create_user(name, age=18, *roles, active=true, **metadata): return { \"name\": name, \"age\": age, \"roles\": roles, \"active\": active, \"metadata\": metadata, } print(create_user(\"asha\", 25, \"admin\", \"editor\", city=\"delhi\")) ``` | syntax | meaning | | --- | --- | | name | required positional/keyword argument | | age=18 | default argument | | *roles | collects extra positional args into tuple | | active=true | keyword-only argument after *roles | | **metadata | collects extra keyword args into dict | ## positional-only and keyword-only arguments ```python def f(a, b, /, c, *, d): print(a, b, c, d) f(1, 2, c=3, d=4) # a and b must be positional # d must be keyword-only ``` useful when designing clean apis. ## first-class functions ```python def shout(text): return text.upper() func = shout print(func(\"hello\")) ``` functions can be assigned, passed as arguments, and returned. ## closures ```python def multiplier(factor): def multiply(value): return value * factor return multiply double = multiplier(2) print(double(10)) # 20 ``` the inner function remembers variables from its enclosing scope. ## decorators a decorator wraps another function. ```python from functools import wraps def log_calls(fn): @wraps(fn) def wrapper(*args, **kwargs): print(f\"calling {fn.__name__}\") result = fn(*args, **kwargs) print(f\"finished {fn.__name__}\") return result return wrapper @log_calls def add(a, b): return a + b print(add(2, 3)) ``` `@log_calls` is equivalent to: ```python add = log_calls(add) ``` ### decorator with arguments ```python from functools import wraps def require_role(role): def decorator(fn): @wraps(fn) def wrapper(user, *args, **kwargs): if role not in user[\"roles\"]: raise permissionerror(\"forbidden\") return fn(user, *args, **kwargs) return wrapper return decorator @require_role(\"admin\") def delete_user(current_user, user_id): return f\"deleted {user_id}\" ``` ## generators generators produce values lazily. ```python def read_large_file(lines): for line in lines: if line.strip(): yield line.strip() for item in read_large_file([\"a\\n\", \"\\n\", \"b\\n\"]): print(item) ``` why useful? - memory efficient - stream processing - infinite sequences - pipelines ## generator expression ```python squares = (x * x for x in range(10)) print(next(squares)) print(next(squares)) ``` ## yield from ```python def chain_lists(lists): for items in lists: yield from items print(list(chain_lists([[1, 2], [3, 4]]))) ``` ## interview questions **q: difference between list comprehension and generator expression?** ```python nums = [x * x for x in range(1_000_000)] # builds list immediately nums_lazy = (x * x for x in range(1_000_000)) # produces lazily ``` use generator expression when you do not need all values in memory at once. **q: why use `functools.wraps` in decorators?** without `wraps`, the wrapped function loses metadata like `__name__`, `__doc__`, annotations, and this can break debugging, docs, and frameworks."
