    "content": "# Python OOP: Classes, Inheritance, MRO, Properties\n\n## Basic class\n\n```python\nclass User:\n    species = \"human\"  # class attribute\n\n    def __init__(self, name, email):\n        self.name = name      # instance attribute\n        self.email = email\n\n    def greet(self):\n        return f\"Hi, I am {self.name}\"\n\nu = User(\"Shelendra\", \"s@example.com\")\nprint(u.greet())\n```\n\n## Class attribute vs instance attribute\n\n```python\nclass Counter:\n    total = 0\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        Counter.total += 1\n\nc1 = Counter()\nc2 = Counter()\nprint(Counter.total)  # 2\n```\n\nBe careful with mutable class attributes:\n\n```python\nclass BadCart:\n    items = []\n\nc1 = BadCart()\nc2 = BadCart()\nc1.items.append(\"book\")\nprint(c2.items)  # ['book'] surprise\n```\n\nCorrect:\n\n```python\nclass Cart:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.items = []\n```\n\n## Instance method, class method, static method\n\n```python\nclass User:\n    domain = \"example.com\"\n\n    def __init__(self, username):\n        self.username = username\n\n    def email(self):\n        return f\"{self.username}@{self.domain}\"\n\n    @classmethod\n    def from_email(cls, email):\n        username = email.split(\"@\")[0]\n        return cls(username)\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def is_valid_email(email):\n        return \"@\" in email\n```\n\n| Method type | First parameter | Use case |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| instance method | self | uses object state |\n| class method | cls | factory methods, class-level behavior |\n| static method | none | utility logically grouped with class |\n\n## Encapsulation in Python\n\nPython does not enforce private fields strongly. It uses conventions:\n\n```python\nclass BankAccount:\n    def __init__(self, balance):\n        self._balance = balance      # protected by convention\n        self.__pin = \"1234\"          # name-mangled\n```\n\n`__pin` becomes `_BankAccount__pin`. This is not security; it prevents accidental collisions.\n\n## Properties\n\n```python\nclass Temperature:\n    def __init__(self, celsius):\n        self.celsius = celsius\n\n    @property\n    def fahrenheit(self):\n        return self.celsius * 9 / 5 + 32\n\n    @fahrenheit.setter\n    def fahrenheit(self, value):\n        self.celsius = (value - 32) * 5 / 9\n\nt = Temperature(0)\nprint(t.fahrenheit)  # 32\n```\n\nProperties allow method-like logic with attribute-like access.\n\n## Inheritance\n\n```python\nclass Animal:\n    def speak(self):\n        return \"sound\"\n\nclass Dog(Animal):\n    def speak(self):\n        return \"bark\"\n```\n\n## super() and MRO\n\n```python\nclass Base:\n    def __init__(self):\n        print(\"Base\")\n\nclass A(Base):\n    def __init__(self):\n        print(\"A\")\n        super().__init__()\n\nclass B(Base):\n    def __init__(self):\n        print(\"B\")\n        super().__init__()\n\nclass C(A, B):\n    def __init__(self):\n        print(\"C\")\n        super().__init__()\n\nC()\nprint(C.mro())\n```\n\nMRO means Method Resolution Order. In multiple inheritance, Python uses C3 linearization.\n\n## Abstract base classes\n\n```python\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n\nclass PaymentGateway(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def charge(self, amount):\n        pass\n\nclass StripeGateway(PaymentGateway):\n    def charge(self, amount):\n        return f\"charged {amount}\"\n```\n\nUseful for enforcing contracts.\n\n## Dataclasses\n\n```python\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True, order=True)\nclass Product:\n    price: float\n    name: str\n    tags: list[str] = field(default_factory=list, compare=False)\n```\n\n`frozen=True` makes it immutable-ish. `default_factory` avoids shared mutable defaults.\n\n## Interview questions\n\n**Q: Composition vs inheritance?**\n\nInheritance means “is-a”. Composition means “has-a”. Prefer composition when behavior can vary independently.\n\n```python\nclass EmailSender:\n    def send(self, message): ...\n\nclass NotificationService:\n    def __init__(self, sender):\n        self.sender = sender\n```\n\nThis makes testing and swapping implementations easier.",
    "searchText": "python python oop: classes, inheritance, mro, properties python oop: classes, inheritance, mro, properties basic class class attribute vs instance attribute be careful with mutable class attributes: correct: instance method, class method, static method method type first parameter use case --- --- --- instance method... # python oop: classes, inheritance, mro, properties ## basic class ```python class user: species = \"human\" # class attribute def __init__(self, name, email): self.name = name # instance attribute self.email = email def greet(self): return f\"hi, i am {self.name}\" u = user(\"shelendra\", \"s@example.com\") print(u.greet()) ``` ## class attribute vs instance attribute ```python class counter: total = 0 def __init__(self): counter.total += 1 c1 = counter() c2 = counter() print(counter.total) # 2 ``` be careful with mutable class attributes: ```python class badcart: items = [] c1 = badcart() c2 = badcart() c1.items.append(\"book\") print(c2.items) # ['book'] surprise ``` correct: ```python class cart: def __init__(self): self.items = [] ``` ## instance method, class method, static method ```python class user: domain = \"example.com\" def __init__(self, username): self.username = username def email(self): return f\"{self.username}@{self.domain}\" @classmethod def from_email(cls, email): username = email.split(\"@\")[0] return cls(username) @staticmethod def is_valid_email(email): return \"@\" in email ``` | method type | first parameter | use case | | --- | --- | --- | | instance method | self | uses object state | | class method | cls | factory methods, class-level behavior | | static method | none | utility logically grouped with class | ## encapsulation in python python does not enforce private fields strongly. it uses conventions: ```python class bankaccount: def __init__(self, balance): self._balance = balance # protected by convention self.__pin = \"1234\" # name-mangled ``` `__pin` becomes `_bankaccount__pin`. this is not security; it prevents accidental collisions. ## properties ```python class temperature: def __init__(self, celsius): self.celsius = celsius @property def fahrenheit(self): return self.celsius * 9 / 5 + 32 @fahrenheit.setter def fahrenheit(self, value): self.celsius = (value - 32) * 5 / 9 t = temperature(0) print(t.fahrenheit) # 32 ``` properties allow method-like logic with attribute-like access. ## inheritance ```python class animal: def speak(self): return \"sound\" class dog(animal): def speak(self): return \"bark\" ``` ## super() and mro ```python class base: def __init__(self): print(\"base\") class a(base): def __init__(self): print(\"a\") super().__init__() class b(base): def __init__(self): print(\"b\") super().__init__() class c(a, b): def __init__(self): print(\"c\") super().__init__() c() print(c.mro()) ``` mro means method resolution order. in multiple inheritance, python uses c3 linearization. ## abstract base classes ```python from abc import abc, abstractmethod class paymentgateway(abc): @abstractmethod def charge(self, amount): pass class stripegateway(paymentgateway): def charge(self, amount): return f\"charged {amount}\" ``` useful for enforcing contracts. ## dataclasses ```python from dataclasses import dataclass, field @dataclass(frozen=true, order=true) class product: price: float name: str tags: list[str] = field(default_factory=list, compare=false) ``` `frozen=true` makes it immutable-ish. `default_factory` avoids shared mutable defaults. ## interview questions **q: composition vs inheritance?** inheritance means “is-a”. composition means “has-a”. prefer composition when behavior can vary independently. ```python class emailsender: def send(self, message): ... class notificationservice: def __init__(self, sender): self.sender = sender ``` this makes testing and swapping implementations easier."
