    "content": "# TypeScript for Full Stack React\n\nTypeScript adds static typing to JavaScript. It helps catch mistakes before runtime.\n\n## Basic types\n\n```ts\nlet name: string = \"Asha\";\nlet age: number = 25;\nlet active: boolean = true;\nlet tags: string[] = [\"react\", \"api\"];\nlet tuple: [string, number] = [\"id\", 1];\n```\n\n## Type alias vs interface\n\n```ts\ntype UserId = string | number;\n\ntype User = {\n  id: UserId;\n  email: string;\n};\n\ninterface Product {\n  id: string;\n  name: string;\n}\n```\n\nBoth can describe object shapes. Interfaces can be declaration-merged; types are more flexible for unions/intersections.\n\n## Union and narrowing\n\n```ts\ntype ApiResult =\n  | { status: \"success\"; data: User }\n  | { status: \"error\"; message: string };\n\nfunction handle(result: ApiResult) {\n  if (result.status === \"success\") {\n    console.log(result.data.email);\n  } else {\n    console.log(result.message);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis is discriminated union. Extremely useful for reducers and API states.\n\n## Generics\n\n```ts\nfunction identity<T>(value: T): T {\n  return value;\n}\n\nconst n = identity<number>(10);\n```\n\n### Generic API response\n\n```ts\ntype ApiResponse<T> = {\n  data: T;\n  error?: string;\n};\n\ntype UserResponse = ApiResponse<User>;\n```\n\n## Utility types\n\n```ts\ntype User = {\n  id: string;\n  email: string;\n  passwordHash: string;\n};\n\ntype PublicUser = Omit<User, \"passwordHash\">;\ntype UserUpdate = Partial<Pick<User, \"email\">>;\ntype RequiredUser = Required<User>;\ntype ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>;\n```\n\n| Utility | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| Partial<T> | all fields optional |\n| Required<T> | all fields required |\n| Pick<T, K> | select fields |\n| Omit<T, K> | remove fields |\n| Readonly<T> | readonly fields |\n| Record<K, V> | object with keys K and values V |\n| ReturnType<F> | function return type |\n| Parameters<F> | function parameter tuple |\n| Awaited<T> | unwrap promise type |\n\n## React props typing\n\n```tsx\ntype ButtonProps = {\n  label: string;\n  onClick: () => void;\n  disabled?: boolean;\n};\n\nfunction Button({ label, onClick, disabled = false }: ButtonProps) {\n  return <button disabled={disabled} onClick={onClick}>{label}</button>;\n}\n```\n\n## Event typing\n\n```tsx\nfunction Form() {\n  const handleChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {\n    console.log(e.target.value);\n  };\n\n  const handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => {\n    e.preventDefault();\n  };\n\n  return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}><input onChange={handleChange} /></form>;\n}\n```\n\n## unknown vs any\n\n```ts\nfunction parse(value: unknown) {\n  if (typeof value === \"string\") {\n    return value.toUpperCase();\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`any` disables type checking. `unknown` forces you to narrow safely.\n\n## never\n\n```ts\nfunction assertNever(x: never): never {\n  throw new Error(\"Unexpected value: \" + x);\n}\n```\n\nUseful for exhaustive switch checking.\n\n## Interview questions\n\n**Q: Why TypeScript if JavaScript works?**\n\nIt catches many bugs earlier, improves refactoring, documents data shapes, improves editor support, and makes large codebases easier to maintain.\n\n**Q: What is type narrowing?**\n\nTypeScript reduces a broad type to a narrower type based on runtime checks like `typeof`, `in`, equality checks, discriminated unions, and custom type guards.\n\n**Q: What are generics?**\n\nGenerics let you write reusable functions/classes/types while preserving the specific type relationship between input and output.",
    "searchText": "typescript typescript for full stack react typescript for full stack react typescript adds static typing to javascript. it helps catch mistakes before runtime. basic types type alias vs interface both can describe object shapes. interfaces can be declaration-merged; types are more flexible for unions/i... # typescript for full stack react typescript adds static typing to javascript. it helps catch mistakes before runtime. ## basic types ```ts let name: string = \"asha\"; let age: number = 25; let active: boolean = true; let tags: string[] = [\"react\", \"api\"]; let tuple: [string, number] = [\"id\", 1]; ``` ## type alias vs interface ```ts type userid = string | number; type user = { id: userid; email: string; }; interface product { id: string; name: string; } ``` both can describe object shapes. interfaces can be declaration-merged; types are more flexible for unions/intersections. ## union and narrowing ```ts type apiresult = | { status: \"success\"; data: user } | { status: \"error\"; message: string }; function handle(result: apiresult) { if (result.status === \"success\") { console.log(result.data.email); } else { console.log(result.message); } } ``` this is discriminated union. extremely useful for reducers and api states. ## generics ```ts function identity<t>(value: t): t { return value; } const n = identity<number>(10); ``` ### generic api response ```ts type apiresponse<t> = { data: t; error?: string; }; type userresponse = apiresponse<user>; ``` ## utility types ```ts type user = { id: string; email: string; passwordhash: string; }; type publicuser = omit<user, \"passwordhash\">; type userupdate = partial<pick<user, \"email\">>; type requireduser = required<user>; type readonlyuser = readonly<user>; ``` | utility | meaning | | --- | --- | | partial<t> | all fields optional | | required<t> | all fields required | | pick<t, k> | select fields | | omit<t, k> | remove fields | | readonly<t> | readonly fields | | record<k, v> | object with keys k and values v | | returntype<f> | function return type | | parameters<f> | function parameter tuple | | awaited<t> | unwrap promise type | ## react props typing ```tsx type buttonprops = { label: string; onclick: () => void; disabled?: boolean; }; function button({ label, onclick, disabled = false }: buttonprops) { return <button disabled={disabled} onclick={onclick}>{label}</button>; } ``` ## event typing ```tsx function form() { const handlechange = (e: react.changeevent<htmlinputelement>) => { console.log(e.target.value); }; const handlesubmit = (e: react.formevent<htmlformelement>) => { e.preventdefault(); }; return <form onsubmit={handlesubmit}><input onchange={handlechange} /></form>; } ``` ## unknown vs any ```ts function parse(value: unknown) { if (typeof value === \"string\") { return value.touppercase(); } } ``` `any` disables type checking. `unknown` forces you to narrow safely. ## never ```ts function assertnever(x: never): never { throw new error(\"unexpected value: \" + x); } ``` useful for exhaustive switch checking. ## interview questions **q: why typescript if javascript works?** it catches many bugs earlier, improves refactoring, documents data shapes, improves editor support, and makes large codebases easier to maintain. **q: what is type narrowing?** typescript reduces a broad type to a narrower type based on runtime checks like `typeof`, `in`, equality checks, discriminated unions, and custom type guards. **q: what are generics?** generics let you write reusable functions/classes/types while preserving the specific type relationship between input and output."
