    "content": "# Full Stack Feature Flow: How to Explain End-to-End Ownership\n\nThe JD says they value someone who can own features end-to-end. Here is how to speak like that.\n\n## Example feature: Create booking\n\n### Frontend\n\n```text\nUser selects trainer/date/time\n  → React validates required fields\n  → Redux/RTK mutation sends POST /bookings\n  → button shows loading\n  → success redirects to booking detail\n  → failure shows useful error\n```\n\n### Backend API\n\n```text\nPOST /bookings\n  → auth middleware validates user\n  → Pydantic/request schema validates body\n  → service checks trainer availability\n  → transaction creates booking\n  → outbox event inserted: booking.created\n  → API returns 201\n```\n\n### Async worker\n\n```text\nOutbox publisher emits event\n  → notification worker sends SMS/email\n  → payment worker creates payment link if needed\n  → status updates stored\n```\n\n### Database\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE bookings (\n    id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id BIGINT NOT NULL,\n    trainer_id BIGINT NOT NULL,\n    starts_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL,\n    ends_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL,\n    status TEXT NOT NULL,\n    created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_bookings_trainer_time\nON bookings(trainer_id, starts_at, ends_at);\n```\n\n### Failure cases to mention\n\n| Failure | Handling |\n| --- | --- |\n| user unauthenticated | 401 |\n| slot already booked | 409 conflict |\n| payment provider down | queue retry/status pending |\n| notification fails | retry worker, do not fail booking |\n| duplicate click | idempotency key |\n| slow DB query | index + explain analyze |\n\n## Production debugging answer structure\n\nWhen asked “How would you debug this?” answer:\n\n1. Clarify expected vs actual behavior.\n2. Reproduce if possible.\n3. Check frontend network request and payload.\n4. Check backend logs with request/correlation ID.\n5. Check DB rows/status transitions.\n6. Check queue/job status and retries.\n7. Check third-party API responses/webhooks.\n8. Identify root cause.\n9. Fix, test, add regression coverage.\n10. Deploy safely and monitor.\n\n## Architecture vocabulary\n\n| Term | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| modular monolith | one deployable app with clean internal modules |\n| microservices | independently deployed services |\n| event-driven | services communicate via events |\n| eventual consistency | data becomes consistent after async processing |\n| idempotency | repeated operation has safe same result |\n| observability | logs, metrics, traces to understand system |\n| backpressure | slow down producers when consumers cannot keep up |\n| circuit breaker | stop calling failing dependency temporarily |\n\n## Interview answer: modular monolith vs microservices\n\nStart with a modular monolith when team/product is small-to-medium. It is simpler to develop, test, deploy, and debug. Split into microservices only when boundaries are clear and independent scaling/deployment is worth the operational complexity.",
    "searchText": "architecture full stack feature flow: how to explain end-to-end ownership full stack feature flow: how to explain end-to-end ownership the jd says they value someone who can own features end-to-end. here is how to speak like that. example feature: create booking frontend backend api async worker database failure cases to mention fai... # full stack feature flow: how to explain end-to-end ownership the jd says they value someone who can own features end-to-end. here is how to speak like that. ## example feature: create booking ### frontend ```text user selects trainer/date/time → react validates required fields → redux/rtk mutation sends post /bookings → button shows loading → success redirects to booking detail → failure shows useful error ``` ### backend api ```text post /bookings → auth middleware validates user → pydantic/request schema validates body → service checks trainer availability → transaction creates booking → outbox event inserted: booking.created → api returns 201 ``` ### async worker ```text outbox publisher emits event → notification worker sends sms/email → payment worker creates payment link if needed → status updates stored ``` ### database ```sql create table bookings ( id bigserial primary key, user_id bigint not null, trainer_id bigint not null, starts_at timestamptz not null, ends_at timestamptz not null, status text not null, created_at timestamptz not null default now() ); create index idx_bookings_trainer_time on bookings(trainer_id, starts_at, ends_at); ``` ### failure cases to mention | failure | handling | | --- | --- | | user unauthenticated | 401 | | slot already booked | 409 conflict | | payment provider down | queue retry/status pending | | notification fails | retry worker, do not fail booking | | duplicate click | idempotency key | | slow db query | index + explain analyze | ## production debugging answer structure when asked “how would you debug this?” answer: 1. clarify expected vs actual behavior. 2. reproduce if possible. 3. check frontend network request and payload. 4. check backend logs with request/correlation id. 5. check db rows/status transitions. 6. check queue/job status and retries. 7. check third-party api responses/webhooks. 8. identify root cause. 9. fix, test, add regression coverage. 10. deploy safely and monitor. ## architecture vocabulary | term | meaning | | --- | --- | | modular monolith | one deployable app with clean internal modules | | microservices | independently deployed services | | event-driven | services communicate via events | | eventual consistency | data becomes consistent after async processing | | idempotency | repeated operation has safe same result | | observability | logs, metrics, traces to understand system | | backpressure | slow down producers when consumers cannot keep up | | circuit breaker | stop calling failing dependency temporarily | ## interview answer: modular monolith vs microservices start with a modular monolith when team/product is small-to-medium. it is simpler to develop, test, deploy, and debug. split into microservices only when boundaries are clear and independent scaling/deployment is worth the operational complexity."
