    "title": "Python Scheduled Jobs: APScheduler, Celery Beat, Cron and Cloud Schedulers",
    "summary": "Python Scheduled Jobs: APScheduler, Celery Beat, Cron and Cloud Schedulers Scheduled jobs are used for reports, reminders, cleanup, syncing third-party data, retrying pending webhooks, cache warming, and billing tasks. Options Option Best for --- --- Cron Simp...",
    "sourceFiles": [
      "full_stack_interview_prep_deep_chatgpt_style_v2(1).html"
    ],
    "content": "# Python Scheduled Jobs: APScheduler, Celery Beat, Cron and Cloud Schedulers\n\nScheduled jobs are used for reports, reminders, cleanup, syncing third-party data, retrying pending webhooks, cache warming, and billing tasks.\n\n## Options\n\n| Option | Best for |\n| --- | --- |\n| Cron | Simple server-level scripts |\n| APScheduler | In-process Python scheduling |\n| Celery Beat | Distributed scheduled jobs with Celery workers |\n| RQ Scheduler | Redis Queue scheduled jobs |\n| Arq | Async Python Redis jobs |\n| Cloud Scheduler/EventBridge | Cloud-native scheduled triggers |\n| Kubernetes CronJob | Containerized scheduled tasks |\n\n## Simple cron script\n\n```bash\n# run every day at 2:30 AM\n30 2 * * * /usr/bin/python3 /app/jobs/cleanup_old_sessions.py >> /var/log/app-cleanup.log 2>&1\n```\n\nGood for simple deployments. Weakness: not very visible unless logging/monitoring is configured.\n\n## APScheduler example\n\n```python\nfrom apscheduler.schedulers.asyncio import AsyncIOScheduler\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nfrom contextlib import asynccontextmanager\n\nscheduler = AsyncIOScheduler()\n\nasync def sync_pending_webhooks():\n    print('sync pending webhooks')\n\n@asynccontextmanager\nasync def lifespan(app: FastAPI):\n    scheduler.add_job(sync_pending_webhooks, 'interval', minutes=5, id='webhook-sync')\n    scheduler.start()\n    yield\n    scheduler.shutdown()\n\napp = FastAPI(lifespan=lifespan)\n```\n\nCaution: if you run multiple app instances, each instance may start the same scheduler. For production, isolate scheduler into one process or use distributed locking.\n\n## Celery Beat style\n\n```python\nfrom celery import Celery\n\ncelery_app = Celery('app', broker='redis://localhost:6379/0')\n\n@celery_app.task\ndef generate_daily_report():\n    print('report generated')\n\ncelery_app.conf.beat_schedule = {\n    'daily-report': {\n        'task': 'generate_daily_report',\n        'schedule': 60 * 60 * 24,\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## FastAPI endpoint enqueueing scheduled-like delayed work\n\n```python\n@app.post('/reminders')\nasync def create_reminder(payload: ReminderCreate):\n    reminder = await save_reminder(payload)\n    await queue.enqueue_at(payload.remind_at, 'send_reminder', reminder.id)\n    return {'id': reminder.id}\n```\n\n## Scheduled job reliability checklist\n\n1. Make jobs idempotent.\n2. Store job status in DB.\n3. Use locking if only one instance should run it.\n4. Add retry/backoff.\n5. Add timeout.\n6. Log start/end/duration/errors.\n7. Alert if job fails repeatedly.\n8. Avoid huge jobs; batch work.\n9. Use cursor/checkpoint for long syncs.\n10. Make reruns safe.\n\n## Example cleanup job\n\n```python\nasync def cleanup_expired_sessions(db):\n    result = await db.execute(\n        text('DELETE FROM sessions WHERE expires_at < now() RETURNING id')\n    )\n    deleted = result.fetchall()\n    await db.commit()\n    logger.info('expired_sessions_deleted', count=len(deleted))\n```\n\n## Interview answer\n\n> For small projects I can use cron or APScheduler. For production distributed systems, I prefer a separate scheduler/worker setup such as Celery Beat, cloud scheduler, or Kubernetes CronJob, with idempotency, locking, retries, and logs.",
    "searchText": "python backend python scheduled jobs: apscheduler, celery beat, cron and cloud schedulers python scheduled jobs: apscheduler, celery beat, cron and cloud schedulers scheduled jobs are used for reports, reminders, cleanup, syncing third-party data, retrying pending webhooks, cache warming, and billing tasks. options option best for --- --- cron simp... # python scheduled jobs: apscheduler, celery beat, cron and cloud schedulers scheduled jobs are used for reports, reminders, cleanup, syncing third-party data, retrying pending webhooks, cache warming, and billing tasks. ## options | option | best for | | --- | --- | | cron | simple server-level scripts | | apscheduler | in-process python scheduling | | celery beat | distributed scheduled jobs with celery workers | | rq scheduler | redis queue scheduled jobs | | arq | async python redis jobs | | cloud scheduler/eventbridge | cloud-native scheduled triggers | | kubernetes cronjob | containerized scheduled tasks | ## simple cron script ```bash # run every day at 2:30 am 30 2 * * * /usr/bin/python3 /app/jobs/cleanup_old_sessions.py >> /var/log/app-cleanup.log 2>&1 ``` good for simple deployments. weakness: not very visible unless logging/monitoring is configured. ## apscheduler example ```python from apscheduler.schedulers.asyncio import asyncioscheduler from fastapi import fastapi from contextlib import asynccontextmanager scheduler = asyncioscheduler() async def sync_pending_webhooks(): print('sync pending webhooks') @asynccontextmanager async def lifespan(app: fastapi): scheduler.add_job(sync_pending_webhooks, 'interval', minutes=5, id='webhook-sync') scheduler.start() yield scheduler.shutdown() app = fastapi(lifespan=lifespan) ``` caution: if you run multiple app instances, each instance may start the same scheduler. for production, isolate scheduler into one process or use distributed locking. ## celery beat style ```python from celery import celery celery_app = celery('app', broker='redis://localhost:6379/0') @celery_app.task def generate_daily_report(): print('report generated') celery_app.conf.beat_schedule = { 'daily-report': { 'task': 'generate_daily_report', 'schedule': 60 * 60 * 24, } } ``` ## fastapi endpoint enqueueing scheduled-like delayed work ```python @app.post('/reminders') async def create_reminder(payload: remindercreate): reminder = await save_reminder(payload) await queue.enqueue_at(payload.remind_at, 'send_reminder', reminder.id) return {'id': reminder.id} ``` ## scheduled job reliability checklist 1. make jobs idempotent. 2. store job status in db. 3. use locking if only one instance should run it. 4. add retry/backoff. 5. add timeout. 6. log start/end/duration/errors. 7. alert if job fails repeatedly. 8. avoid huge jobs; batch work. 9. use cursor/checkpoint for long syncs. 10. make reruns safe. ## example cleanup job ```python async def cleanup_expired_sessions(db): result = await db.execute( text('delete from sessions where expires_at < now() returning id') ) deleted = result.fetchall() await db.commit() logger.info('expired_sessions_deleted', count=len(deleted)) ``` ## interview answer > for small projects i can use cron or apscheduler. for production distributed systems, i prefer a separate scheduler/worker setup such as celery beat, cloud scheduler, or kubernetes cronjob, with idempotency, locking, retries, and logs."
