    "summary": "PART H - AWS Glue and ETL 32. What is Glue? ! Glue Studio Job details: script path, metrics, continuous logging, Spark UI https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/glue/latest/dg/images/job-details-script-location-params-screenshot.png - Shows real Glue Studio Job de...",
    "sourceFiles": [
      "updated_interview_notes(1).html"
    ],
    "content": "# PART H - AWS Glue and ETL\n\n## 32. What is Glue?\n\n![Glue Studio Job details: script path, metrics, continuous logging, Spark UI](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/glue/latest/dg/images/job-details-script-location-params-screenshot.png)\n\n- Shows real Glue Studio Job details tab with script filename/path and observability options.\n- For interviews, focus on worker type, worker count, bookmarks, temp path, logs, Spark UI, job parameters.\n- For slow/OOM Glue jobs: check partitions, skew, shuffle, joins, small files, and output format.\n\nAWS Glue is a managed ETL service often used with Spark, Data Catalog, Crawlers, S3, and jobs.\n\n### Glue components\n\n| Component | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| Crawler | scans data and creates/updates catalog tables |\n| Data Catalog | metadata store for tables/schemas/partitions |\n| Job | ETL script execution |\n| DynamicFrame | Glue abstraction over semi-structured data |\n| Spark DataFrame | Spark native distributed data structure |\n| Bookmark | tracks processed data for incremental ETL |\n| Worker | compute resource for Glue job |\n\n### Glue flow\n\n```text\nS3 raw data\n  -> Crawler updates Data Catalog\n  -> Glue ETL job reads catalog/S3\n  -> transforms data\n  -> writes partitioned Parquet to curated S3\n  -> Athena/Redshift/app consumes output\n```\n\n### Glue job skeleton\n\n```python\nimport sys\nfrom awsglue.context import GlueContext\nfrom awsglue.job import Job\nfrom awsglue.utils import getResolvedOptions\nfrom pyspark.context import SparkContext\n\nargs = getResolvedOptions(sys.argv, [\"JOB_NAME\"])\n\nsc = SparkContext()\nglue_context = GlueContext(sc)\nspark = glue_context.spark_session\njob = Job(glue_context)\njob.init(args[\"JOB_NAME\"], args)\n\nsource = glue_context.create_dynamic_frame.from_catalog(\n    database=\"raw_db\",\n    table_name=\"invoices\"\n)\n\nmapped = source.apply_mapping([\n    (\"invoice_id\", \"string\", \"invoice_id\", \"string\"),\n    (\"amount\", \"double\", \"amount\", \"double\"),\n])\n\nglue_context.write_dynamic_frame.from_options(\n    frame=mapped,\n    connection_type=\"s3\",\n    connection_options={\"path\": \"s3://bucket/curated/invoices/\"},\n    format=\"parquet\",\n)\n\njob.commit()\n```\n\n### Glue bookmarks\n\nBookmarks help process only new data. But they depend on proper configuration and transformation context.\n\nCommon problem:\n\n```text\nJob bookmark enabled but transformation_ctx missing\n  -> bookmark may not track source as expected\n```\n\n### Glue scaling issues\n\n| Issue | Cause | Fix |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Driver OOM | too many files/partitions listed | partition better, use Glue S3 lister, compact files |\n| Slow job startup | Glue environment provisioning | use for batch, not low-latency APIs |\n| Many small files | Spark task overhead | compact into larger Parquet files |\n| Schema mismatch | crawler inferred wrong schema | enforce schema, validate input |\n| Skewed data | few keys dominate processing | salting, repartitioning, better keys |\n| Job reprocesses old files | bookmarks not configured correctly | enable bookmarks, set transformation_ctx |\n| Expensive jobs | over-provisioned workers or bad partitions | tune worker type/count, partition pruning |\n\nLead answer:\n\n> \"For Glue, I think in terms of file size, partitioning, schema evolution, bookmarks, worker sizing, and Spark execution behavior. Most Glue issues are not coding issues only; they are data layout and distributed processing issues.\"\n\n---",
    "searchText": "aws lead source expansion h - aws glue and etl part h - aws glue and etl 32. what is glue? ! glue studio job details: script path, metrics, continuous logging, spark ui https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/glue/latest/dg/images/job-details-script-location-params-screenshot.png - shows real glue studio job de... # part h - aws glue and etl ## 32. what is glue? ![glue studio job details: script path, metrics, continuous logging, spark ui](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/images/glue/latest/dg/images/job-details-script-location-params-screenshot.png) - shows real glue studio job details tab with script filename/path and observability options. - for interviews, focus on worker type, worker count, bookmarks, temp path, logs, spark ui, job parameters. - for slow/oom glue jobs: check partitions, skew, shuffle, joins, small files, and output format. aws glue is a managed etl service often used with spark, data catalog, crawlers, s3, and jobs. ### glue components | component | meaning | | --- | --- | | crawler | scans data and creates/updates catalog tables | | data catalog | metadata store for tables/schemas/partitions | | job | etl script execution | | dynamicframe | glue abstraction over semi-structured data | | spark dataframe | spark native distributed data structure | | bookmark | tracks processed data for incremental etl | | worker | compute resource for glue job | ### glue flow ```text s3 raw data -> crawler updates data catalog -> glue etl job reads catalog/s3 -> transforms data -> writes partitioned parquet to curated s3 -> athena/redshift/app consumes output ``` ### glue job skeleton ```python import sys from awsglue.context import gluecontext from awsglue.job import job from awsglue.utils import getresolvedoptions from pyspark.context import sparkcontext args = getresolvedoptions(sys.argv, [\"job_name\"]) sc = sparkcontext() glue_context = gluecontext(sc) spark = glue_context.spark_session job = job(glue_context) job.init(args[\"job_name\"], args) source = glue_context.create_dynamic_frame.from_catalog( database=\"raw_db\", table_name=\"invoices\" ) mapped = source.apply_mapping([ (\"invoice_id\", \"string\", \"invoice_id\", \"string\"), (\"amount\", \"double\", \"amount\", \"double\"), ]) glue_context.write_dynamic_frame.from_options( frame=mapped, connection_type=\"s3\", connection_options={\"path\": \"s3://bucket/curated/invoices/\"}, format=\"parquet\", ) job.commit() ``` ### glue bookmarks bookmarks help process only new data. but they depend on proper configuration and transformation context. common problem: ```text job bookmark enabled but transformation_ctx missing -> bookmark may not track source as expected ``` ### glue scaling issues | issue | cause | fix | | --- | --- | --- | | driver oom | too many files/partitions listed | partition better, use glue s3 lister, compact files | | slow job startup | glue environment provisioning | use for batch, not low-latency apis | | many small files | spark task overhead | compact into larger parquet files | | schema mismatch | crawler inferred wrong schema | enforce schema, validate input | | skewed data | few keys dominate processing | salting, repartitioning, better keys | | job reprocesses old files | bookmarks not configured correctly | enable bookmarks, set transformation_ctx | | expensive jobs | over-provisioned workers or bad partitions | tune worker type/count, partition pruning | lead answer: > \"for glue, i think in terms of file size, partitioning, schema evolution, bookmarks, worker sizing, and spark execution behavior. most glue issues are not coding issues only; they are data layout and distributed processing issues.\" ---"
