    "content": "# PART I - Containers, EC2, ECS, EKS\n\n## 33. EC2 basics\n\nEC2 is virtual machine compute.\n\nUse EC2 when:\n\n- you need OS-level control\n- long-running process\n- custom runtime\n- background worker not suitable for Lambda\n- vendor software\n- legacy app\n\n### EC2 production checklist\n\n- Use private subnets behind ALB where possible.\n- Use security groups, not open `0.0.0.0/0` SSH.\n- Use SSM Session Manager instead of SSH where possible.\n- Install CloudWatch agent for logs/metrics.\n- Use Auto Scaling Group for HA.\n- Use AMI/user-data/IaC for repeatable provisioning.\n- Patch regularly.\n\n---\n\n## 34. ECS/Fargate\n\nECS runs containers. Fargate runs containers without managing EC2 hosts.\n\n```text\nDocker image -> ECR -> ECS Task Definition -> ECS Service -> Tasks\n```\n\n### ECS terms\n\n| Term | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| Cluster | logical group of compute |\n| Task definition | blueprint for container CPU/memory/env/logs |\n| Task | running instance of task definition |\n| Service | keeps desired number of tasks running |\n| Fargate | serverless compute for containers |\n| ECR | container registry |\n\nUse ECS/Fargate when:\n\n- API runs longer than Lambda max duration\n- You need web server process\n- You need more control than Lambda\n- You have containerized FastAPI/Flask\n\n### Scaling\n\n```text\nALB request count / CPU / memory / custom metric\n  -> ECS Service Auto Scaling\n  -> desired task count increases/decreases\n```\n\nCommon issues:\n\n| Symptom | Cause |\n| --- | --- |\n| Task keeps restarting | app crash, wrong command, health check fail |\n| Cannot pull image | task execution role/ECR permission/network |\n| Cannot reach DB | SG/subnet/route issue |\n| Logs missing | awslogs config/role issue |\n| Deployment stuck | health check, min/max healthy percent |\n\n---\n\n## 35. EKS/Kubernetes basics\n\nYou only need enough for interview unless role is Kubernetes-heavy.\n\n| K8s concept | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| Pod | smallest deployable unit |\n| Deployment | manages replicas/rollouts |\n| Service | stable network endpoint |\n| Ingress | HTTP routing into cluster |\n| ConfigMap | non-secret config |\n| Secret | sensitive config |\n| HPA | scales pods horizontally |\n| Node | worker machine |\n| Namespace | logical isolation |\n\n### Kubernetes deployment idea\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: fastapi-app\nspec:\n  replicas: 3\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: fastapi-app\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: fastapi-app\n    spec:\n      containers:\n        - name: app\n          image: example/fastapi-app:1.0\n          ports:\n            - containerPort: 8000\n```\n\nLead answer:\n\n> \"For Kubernetes, I focus on health checks, resource requests/limits, horizontal pod autoscaling, rolling deployments, config/secrets, ingress, and observability. Kubernetes solves orchestration, but it also adds operational complexity.\"\n\n---",
    "searchText": "aws lead source expansion i - containers, ec2, ecs, eks part i - containers, ec2, ecs, eks 33. ec2 basics ec2 is virtual machine compute. use ec2 when: - you need os-level control - long-running process - custom runtime - background worker not suitable for lambda - vendor software - legacy app ec2 production checkl... # part i - containers, ec2, ecs, eks ## 33. ec2 basics ec2 is virtual machine compute. use ec2 when: - you need os-level control - long-running process - custom runtime - background worker not suitable for lambda - vendor software - legacy app ### ec2 production checklist - use private subnets behind alb where possible. - use security groups, not open `0.0.0.0/0` ssh. - use ssm session manager instead of ssh where possible. - install cloudwatch agent for logs/metrics. - use auto scaling group for ha. - use ami/user-data/iac for repeatable provisioning. - patch regularly. --- ## 34. ecs/fargate ecs runs containers. fargate runs containers without managing ec2 hosts. ```text docker image -> ecr -> ecs task definition -> ecs service -> tasks ``` ### ecs terms | term | meaning | | --- | --- | | cluster | logical group of compute | | task definition | blueprint for container cpu/memory/env/logs | | task | running instance of task definition | | service | keeps desired number of tasks running | | fargate | serverless compute for containers | | ecr | container registry | use ecs/fargate when: - api runs longer than lambda max duration - you need web server process - you need more control than lambda - you have containerized fastapi/flask ### scaling ```text alb request count / cpu / memory / custom metric -> ecs service auto scaling -> desired task count increases/decreases ``` common issues: | symptom | cause | | --- | --- | | task keeps restarting | app crash, wrong command, health check fail | | cannot pull image | task execution role/ecr permission/network | | cannot reach db | sg/subnet/route issue | | logs missing | awslogs config/role issue | | deployment stuck | health check, min/max healthy percent | --- ## 35. eks/kubernetes basics you only need enough for interview unless role is kubernetes-heavy. | k8s concept | meaning | | --- | --- | | pod | smallest deployable unit | | deployment | manages replicas/rollouts | | service | stable network endpoint | | ingress | http routing into cluster | | configmap | non-secret config | | secret | sensitive config | | hpa | scales pods horizontally | | node | worker machine | | namespace | logical isolation | ### kubernetes deployment idea ```yaml apiversion: apps/v1 kind: deployment metadata: name: fastapi-app spec: replicas: 3 selector: matchlabels: app: fastapi-app template: metadata: labels: app: fastapi-app spec: containers: - name: app image: example/fastapi-app:1.0 ports: - containerport: 8000 ``` lead answer: > \"for kubernetes, i focus on health checks, resource requests/limits, horizontal pod autoscaling, rolling deployments, config/secrets, ingress, and observability. kubernetes solves orchestration, but it also adds operational complexity.\" ---"
