    "content": "# PART L - Deployment, CI/CD, IaC\n\n## 47. Deployment options\n\n| Workload | Deployment style |\n| --- | --- |\n| Lambda | SAM/CDK/Terraform/Serverless Framework |\n| FastAPI container | Docker + ECS/Fargate/EKS/App Runner |\n| Glue | Glue job script + job config + IaC |\n| Static frontend | S3 + CloudFront |\n| Batch script | Lambda, ECS scheduled task, Glue, Batch |\n\n### Lambda deployment checklist\n\n- Environment variables configured.\n- Secrets not stored in plain env if sensitive; use Secrets Manager/KMS.\n- IAM role least privilege.\n- Memory/timeout tuned.\n- DLQ/destination configured for async.\n- Logs and alarms created.\n- Version/alias strategy for safe deployment.\n- Rollback plan.\n\n### Blue/green with Lambda alias\n\n```text\nVersion 10 = current stable\nVersion 11 = new release\nAlias prod shifts 10% traffic to v11\nMonitor errors/duration\nShift 100% or rollback\n```\n\n---\n\n## 48. Infrastructure as Code\n\nLead-level answer:\n\n> \"For repeatable environments, I prefer IaC. Manual console changes are useful for exploration but risky for production because they are hard to review, reproduce, and rollback.\"\n\nTools:\n\n- AWS SAM for serverless apps\n- AWS CDK for code-defined AWS infra\n- Terraform for multi-cloud/team-standard IaC\n- CloudFormation as AWS-native foundation\n\n---",
