    "content": "# PART N - Python + AWS Code Patterns\n\n## 50. Boto3 client config and retries\n\n```python\nimport boto3\nfrom botocore.config import Config\n\nconfig = Config(\n    region_name=\"ap-south-1\",\n    retries={\"max_attempts\": 5, \"mode\": \"standard\"},\n    connect_timeout=3,\n    read_timeout=30,\n)\n\ns3 = boto3.client(\"s3\", config=config)\n```\n\n### Client vs resource\n\n| Client | Resource |\n| --- | --- |\n| low-level API style | object-oriented abstraction |\n| exposes newer service features sooner | easier for some common operations |\n| response dictionaries | resource objects |\n\nLead answer:\n\n> \"I generally use clients for production service integrations because they map closely to AWS APIs and expose service features consistently.\"\n\n---\n\n## 51. Paginators\n\nMany AWS APIs return paginated results.\n\n```python\npaginator = s3.get_paginator(\"list_objects_v2\")\n\nfor page in paginator.paginate(Bucket=\"my-bucket\", Prefix=\"raw/\"):\n    for obj in page.get(\"Contents\", []):\n        print(obj[\"Key\"])\n```\n\nNever assume one `list_objects_v2` call returns all objects.\n\n---\n\n## 52. Waiters\n\nWaiters poll until a resource reaches a desired state.\n\n```python\nec2 = boto3.client(\"ec2\")\nwaiter = ec2.get_waiter(\"instance_running\")\nwaiter.wait(InstanceIds=[\"i-1234567890abcdef0\"])\n```\n\nUse waiters instead of manual sleep loops when available.\n\n---\n\n## 53. Idempotent worker pattern\n\n```python\ndef process_job(job_id):\n    job = repository.get(job_id)\n\n    if job.status == \"COMPLETED\":\n        return job.result\n\n    repository.mark_processing(job_id)\n\n    try:\n        result = external_processing(job)\n        repository.mark_completed(job_id, result)\n        return result\n    except Exception as exc:\n        repository.mark_failed(job_id, str(exc))\n        raise\n```\n\nIdempotency keys can be:\n\n- job ID\n- S3 bucket + key + version ID\n- external request ID\n- event ID\n- hash of payload\n\n---\n\n## 54. Structured logging pattern\n\n```python\nimport json\nimport logging\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger()\nlogger.setLevel(logging.INFO)\n\ndef log_event(message, **kwargs):\n    logger.info(json.dumps({\"message\": message, **kwargs}))\n\ndef handler(event, context):\n    log_event(\n        \"lambda_started\",\n        request_id=context.aws_request_id,\n        function=context.function_name,\n    )\n```\n\n---",
    "searchText": "aws lead source expansion n - python + aws code patterns part n - python + aws code patterns 50. boto3 client config and retries client vs resource client resource --- --- low-level api style object-oriented abstraction exposes newer service features sooner easier for some common operations response dictionaries res... # part n - python + aws code patterns ## 50. boto3 client config and retries ```python import boto3 from botocore.config import config config = config( region_name=\"ap-south-1\", retries={\"max_attempts\": 5, \"mode\": \"standard\"}, connect_timeout=3, read_timeout=30, ) s3 = boto3.client(\"s3\", config=config) ``` ### client vs resource | client | resource | | --- | --- | | low-level api style | object-oriented abstraction | | exposes newer service features sooner | easier for some common operations | | response dictionaries | resource objects | lead answer: > \"i generally use clients for production service integrations because they map closely to aws apis and expose service features consistently.\" --- ## 51. paginators many aws apis return paginated results. ```python paginator = s3.get_paginator(\"list_objects_v2\") for page in paginator.paginate(bucket=\"my-bucket\", prefix=\"raw/\"): for obj in page.get(\"contents\", []): print(obj[\"key\"]) ``` never assume one `list_objects_v2` call returns all objects. --- ## 52. waiters waiters poll until a resource reaches a desired state. ```python ec2 = boto3.client(\"ec2\") waiter = ec2.get_waiter(\"instance_running\") waiter.wait(instanceids=[\"i-1234567890abcdef0\"]) ``` use waiters instead of manual sleep loops when available. --- ## 53. idempotent worker pattern ```python def process_job(job_id): job = repository.get(job_id) if job.status == \"completed\": return job.result repository.mark_processing(job_id) try: result = external_processing(job) repository.mark_completed(job_id, result) return result except exception as exc: repository.mark_failed(job_id, str(exc)) raise ``` idempotency keys can be: - job id - s3 bucket + key + version id - external request id - event id - hash of payload --- ## 54. structured logging pattern ```python import json import logging logger = logging.getlogger() logger.setlevel(logging.info) def log_event(message, **kwargs): logger.info(json.dumps({\"message\": message, **kwargs})) def handler(event, context): log_event( \"lambda_started\", request_id=context.aws_request_id, function=context.function_name, ) ``` ---"
