    "content": "# PART V2-F - Step Functions Deep Dive\n\n## 28. Why Step Functions\n\nStep Functions orchestrates workflows. It is useful when multiple steps need state, retries, branching, waiting, or visibility.\n\nUse Step Functions when:\n\n```text\n- workflow has multiple dependent steps\n- human-readable execution history is useful\n- each step may need retry/catch\n- long-running orchestration is needed\n- parallel/map processing is needed\n```\n\nDo not use Step Functions for everything:\n\n```text\n- very simple single-step async jobs may only need SQS + Lambda\n- ultra-high-frequency tiny events may be cost-sensitive\n```\n\n### Standard vs Express\n\n| Type | Best for |\n| --- | --- |\n| Standard | Long-running, auditable workflows, exactly-once workflow execution semantics |\n| Express | High-volume short-duration workflows, lower cost for high throughput |\n\n---\n\n## 29. Retry and Catch\n\nStep Functions can retry failed states and then catch errors if retries are exhausted.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"StartAt\": \"ProcessFile\",\n  \"States\": {\n    \"ProcessFile\": {\n      \"Type\": \"Task\",\n      \"Resource\": \"arn:aws:lambda:ap-south-1:123:function:process-file\",\n      \"Retry\": [\n        {\n          \"ErrorEquals\": [\"Lambda.ServiceException\", \"Lambda.TooManyRequestsException\"],\n          \"IntervalSeconds\": 2,\n          \"MaxAttempts\": 3,\n          \"BackoffRate\": 2.0\n        }\n      ],\n      \"Catch\": [\n        {\n          \"ErrorEquals\": [\"States.ALL\"],\n          \"Next\": \"MarkFailed\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"Next\": \"MarkSuccess\"\n    },\n    \"MarkFailed\": {\"Type\": \"Pass\", \"End\": true},\n    \"MarkSuccess\": {\"Type\": \"Pass\", \"End\": true}\n  }\n}\n```\n\nLead answer:\n\n> \"I use Step Functions when I need workflow visibility and step-level retry/catch. I keep each Lambda step idempotent because retries can execute a step again.\"\n\n---\n\n## 30. Distributed Map use case\n\nFor thousands or millions of items:\n\n```text\nS3 manifest/list -> Distributed Map -> process each object -> aggregate results\n```\n\nConsiderations:\n\n```text\n- concurrency limit\n- downstream service throttling\n- per-item idempotency\n- failure tolerance\n- output location\n- cost of state transitions\n```\n\n---",
    "searchText": "aws lead source expansion advanced f - step functions deep dive part v2-f - step functions deep dive 28. why step functions step functions orchestrates workflows. it is useful when multiple steps need state, retries, branching, waiting, or visibility. use step functions when: do not use step functions for everything: stand... # part v2-f - step functions deep dive ## 28. why step functions step functions orchestrates workflows. it is useful when multiple steps need state, retries, branching, waiting, or visibility. use step functions when: ```text - workflow has multiple dependent steps - human-readable execution history is useful - each step may need retry/catch - long-running orchestration is needed - parallel/map processing is needed ``` do not use step functions for everything: ```text - very simple single-step async jobs may only need sqs + lambda - ultra-high-frequency tiny events may be cost-sensitive ``` ### standard vs express | type | best for | | --- | --- | | standard | long-running, auditable workflows, exactly-once workflow execution semantics | | express | high-volume short-duration workflows, lower cost for high throughput | --- ## 29. retry and catch step functions can retry failed states and then catch errors if retries are exhausted. ```json { \"startat\": \"processfile\", \"states\": { \"processfile\": { \"type\": \"task\", \"resource\": \"arn:aws:lambda:ap-south-1:123:function:process-file\", \"retry\": [ { \"errorequals\": [\"lambda.serviceexception\", \"lambda.toomanyrequestsexception\"], \"intervalseconds\": 2, \"maxattempts\": 3, \"backoffrate\": 2.0 } ], \"catch\": [ { \"errorequals\": [\"states.all\"], \"next\": \"markfailed\" } ], \"next\": \"marksuccess\" }, \"markfailed\": {\"type\": \"pass\", \"end\": true}, \"marksuccess\": {\"type\": \"pass\", \"end\": true} } } ``` lead answer: > \"i use step functions when i need workflow visibility and step-level retry/catch. i keep each lambda step idempotent because retries can execute a step again.\" --- ## 30. distributed map use case for thousands or millions of items: ```text s3 manifest/list -> distributed map -> process each object -> aggregate results ``` considerations: ```text - concurrency limit - downstream service throttling - per-item idempotency - failure tolerance - output location - cost of state transitions ``` ---"
