    "content": "# PART V2-P - Cost Optimization\n\n## 69. Lambda cost levers\n\n```text\ncost roughly depends on requests + duration * memory\n```\n\nOptimization:\n\n```text\n- reduce duration\n- tune memory for better CPU\n- avoid unnecessary invocations\n- batch SQS records\n- avoid recursive triggers\n- use provisioned concurrency only where needed\n```\n\n---\n\n## 70. Glue cost levers\n\n```text\n- DPU hours\n- worker type/count\n- job duration\n- inefficient transformations\n- small files\n- repeated full reprocessing\n```\n\nOptimization:\n\n```text\n- bookmarks/incremental loads\n- partition pruning\n- Parquet instead of CSV\n- filter early\n- right-size worker type\n- compact small files\n```\n\n---\n\n## 71. NAT Gateway hidden cost\n\nNAT Gateway can become expensive when private subnets send large traffic through it.\n\nMitigation:\n\n```text\n- use S3 Gateway Endpoint\n- use DynamoDB Gateway Endpoint\n- use Interface VPC Endpoints for supported services\n- avoid routing heavy AWS-service traffic through NAT\n```\n\nLead answer:\n\n> \"If I see unexpected network cost, I check NAT Gateway data processing, cross-AZ traffic, cross-region traffic, and whether VPC endpoints should be used.\"\n\n---",
